    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-03-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-03-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="184"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d184">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">600.0012/3–1854</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Deputy Assistant Secretary of State for
                        United Nations Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_WAINHOUSEDW1" type="from"
                            >Wainhouse</persName>) to the United States Representative at the United
                        Nations (<persName corresp="#p_LODGEHCJ1" type="to">Lodge</persName>)</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d184fn1">Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_BECHHOEFERBG1"
                            >Bechhoefer</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_MEYERSH1"
                            >Meyers</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-03-20">March 20,
                            1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <item>Subject:</item>
                    <item>Progress in Implementing the President’s December 8 Proposals</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Your memorandum of March 18<note n="2" xml:id="d184fn2">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1376">p.
                            1376</ref>.</note> asks when action may be expected to implement the
                        President’s proposals, particularly steps “to hasten the day when fear of
                        the atom will begin to disappear from the minds of people…”. Action on this
                        matter is progressing along two lines: private discussions with the USSR on
                        the peaceful uses of atomic energy, and a U.S. governmental review of our
                        basic policies on disarmament.</item>
                    <pb facs="0564" n="1378" xml:id="pg_1378"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>The private discussions with the USSR on peaceful uses of atomic energy
                        have progressed to the point where, as you know, the Secretary handed Soviet
                        Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_ZARUBINGN1">Zarubin</persName> on March 19
                        a copy of our tentative views outlining the organization and functions of an
                        International Atomic Energy Agency.<note n="3" xml:id="d184fn3">For text,
                            see <ref target="#pg_1372">p. 1372</ref>.</note> I enclose a copy of
                        this outline for your own information. Prior to its transmittal to the USSR,
                        the outline was discussed with <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>, French and
                        Canadian representatives and their general concurrence obtained to the
                        document. The details of this outline have not been made public.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>The review of basic disarmament policy is now taking place with the
                        participation of the State Department, Department of Defense, Atomic Energy
                        Commission and <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss>. The most recent
                        developments in connection with this matter are reflected in <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Action #1035, dated February 11, 1954:
                            <quote rend="blockquote">
                            <p rend="flushleft">“<hi rend="italic">U.S. Position With Respect to the
                                    Regulation, Limitation and Balanced Reduction of Armed Forces
                                    and Armaments</hi> (<gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Action
                                Nos. 899–c and 959–a; <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 112)<note
                                    n="4" xml:id="d184fn4">For <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                                    Action Nos. 899 and 959, see footnotes 3 and 4, <ref
                                        target="#pg_1212">pp. 1212</ref> and <ref target="#pg_1246"
                                        >1246</ref>, respectively; for <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                                        >NSC</gloss> 112, July 6, 1951, see <ref
                                        target="frus1951v01#pg_477">
                                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1951, vol. <hi
                                            rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 477</ref>.</note>
                            </p>
                            <list>
                                <label>a.</label>
                                <item>Noted an oral report by Mr. <persName corresp="#p_CUTLERR1"
                                        >Cutler</persName> on the status of the work of the Special
                                    Committee appointed to review the current policy contained in
                                        <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 112, with particular
                                    reference to the international control of atomic energy,
                                    pursuant to <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Action No.
                                    899–c.</item>
                                <label>b.</label>
                                <item>Noted the President’s desire that the above-mentioned Special
                                    Committee expedite the completion of its review of the policy
                                    contained in <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 112 and report
                                    to the Council its findings and recommendations thereon.”</item>
                            </list>
                        </quote>
                    </item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>We are informed that even with maximum expediting of this review, it will
                        take several months before it can be completed.<note n="5" xml:id="d184fn5">
                            <p>In a letter of Mar. 25, <persName corresp="#p_LODGEHCJ1"
                                    >Lodge</persName> responded to <persName
                                    corresp="#p_WAINHOUSEDW1">Wainhouse</persName> as follows:
                                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>“Dear Dave: I received your top secret memorandum of March
                                        20th.</p>
                                    <p>“Frankly, it is not very enlightening and does not give me
                                        much that I can tell the Ambassadors here.</p>
                                    <p>“I think this President’s speech of December 8 made it
                                        perfectly clear that he was in a tremendous hurry to get
                                        this thing started. Nothing in your memorandum indicates any
                                        hurry or any intention to hurry.</p>
                                    <p>“Unless I hear any news from you to the contrary, I must
                                        merely give evasive answers and stalls when I get questions
                                        here.</p>
                                    <p>“In the light of the tremendous impression which the
                                        President’s speech made on December 8 this is rather a
                                        pitiful anti-climax.” (<gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>
                                        files)</p>
                                </quote>
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </item>
                </list>
            </div>
